‘’’Rio de Janeiro’’’ (oetsprekn as ‘’RIE-jo de zja-NEA-ro’’, [[Portugees|Portugese]] oetsproake {{IPA|ˈʁi.u dʒi ʒɐˈnejɾu}}) of mangs ook kortweg ‘’’Rio’’’, is de tweede grötste stad van [[Brazilië]]. Et is de heuwdstad van de [[Rio de Janeiro (deelstoat)|lieknamigen deelstoat]]. Delen van de stad stoat op de [[wereldarfgoodlieste|wearldoarfgoodlieste]] van [[UNESCO]].<ref>[http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1100 UNESCO - Rio de Janeiro: Carioca Landscapes between the Mountain and the Sea. 1 July 2012].</ref>
De stad wör in [[1556]] egroondt duur et [[Portugese Riek]]. Et was doaroonder anvaankelik de heuwdstad van et [[Kapteinskoppen van et Portugese Riek|Kapteinskop Rio de Janeiro]]. In [[1763]] wör et de heuwdstad van de [[Stoat Brazilië]], nen stoat oonder et Portugese Riek. Toen as in [[1808]] et [[Brazilië#Verenigd_Keuninkriek_met_Portugal|Portugese Hof noar Brazilië oetweek]], wör Rio de wonstad van Keunigin [[Maria I van Portugal]] öar hof. Doar maakten zee met öar zönne, den [[preensregeant]] en anstoanden keunink [[Johan VI van Portugal]] van Brazilië een keuninkriek binnen et [[Verenigd Keuninkriek van Portugal, Brazilië en de Algarven]]. 
Rio stayed the capital of the [[pluricontinentalism|pluricontinental]] Lusitanian monarchy until 1822, when the [[War of Independence of Brazil|War of Brazilian Independence]] began. This is one of the few instances in history that the capital of a colonising country officially shifted to a city in one of its colonies. Rio de Janeiro subsequently served as the capital of the independent monarchy, the [[Empire of Brazil]], until 1889, and then the capital of a republican Brazil until 1960 when the capital was transferred to [[Brasília]].

Rio de Janeiro has the second largest municipal GDP in the country,<ref name="IBGE_PIB_Ranking">{{cite web |url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/estatistica/economia/pibmunicipios/2006/tab02.pdf |publisher=Instituto Brasileiro de Geografia e Estatística (IBGE) |title=Posição ocupada pelos 100 maiores municípios em relação ao Produto Interno Bruto |date=16 December 2008 |accessdate=16 December 2008}}</ref> and 30th largest in the world in 2008,<ref name="Richest_Cities">{{cite web |url=http://www.citymayors.com/statistics/richest-cities-2005.html |publisher=City Mayors Statistics |title=The 150 richest cities in the world by GDP in 2005 |date=11 March 2007 |accessdate=8 September 2008}}</ref> estimated at about [[Brazilian real|R$]]343&nbsp;billion (IBGE, 2008) (nearly US$201&nbsp;billion). It is headquarters to Brazilian oil, mining, and telecommunications companies, including two of the country's major corporations—[[Petrobras]] and [[Vale (mining company)|Vale]]—and Latin America's largest telemedia conglomerate, [[Organizações Globo|Grupo Globo]]. The home of many universities and institutes, it is the second-largest center of research and development in Brazil, accounting for 17% of national scientific output according to 2005 data.<ref name="Unicamp_2005">{{cite web |url=http://www.unicamp.br/unicamp/canal_aberto/clipping/junho2005/clipping050617_correiopop.html |publisher=Universidade Estadual de Campinas (Unicamp) |title=Assessoria de Comunicação e Imprensa |date=17 June 2005 |accessdate=8 September 2008 |archiveurl=//web.archive.org/web/20080617115727/http://www.unicamp.br/unicamp/canal_aberto/clipping/junho2005/clipping050617_correiopop.html |archivedate=17 June 2008}}{{dead link|date=February 2016}}</ref>

Rio de Janeiro is one of the most visited cities in the [[Southern Hemisphere]] and is known for its natural settings, [[Brazilian Carnival|Carnival]], [[samba]], [[bossa nova]], and [[balneario]] beaches<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/player/nol/newsid_8250000/newsid_8250700/8250788.stm?bw=bb&mp=wm&news=1&nol_storyid=8250788&bbcws=1 "Rio de Janeiro's Beach Culture"] Tayfun King, ''Fast Track'', BBC World News (11 September 2009)</ref> such as [[Barra da Tijuca, Rio de Janeiro|Barra da Tijuca]], [[Copacabana (Rio de Janeiro)|Copacabana]], [[Ipanema, Rio de Janeiro|Ipanema]], and [[Leblon, Rio de Janeiro|Leblon]]. In addition to the beaches, some of the most famous landmarks include the giant statue of [[Christ the Redeemer (statue)|Christ the Redeemer]] atop [[Corcovado]] mountain, named one of the [[New7Wonders of the World|New Seven Wonders of the World]]; [[Sugarloaf Mountain (Brazil)|Sugarloaf Mountain]] with its [[cable car]]; the ''[[Sambadrome Marquês de Sapucaí|Sambódromo]]'' (Sambadrome), a permanent grandstand-lined parade avenue which is used during Carnival; and [[Maracanã Stadium]], one of the [[List of association football stadiums by capacity|world's largest football stadiums]].

Rio de Janeiro will host the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] and the [[2016 Summer Paralympics]]—the first time a South American and [[List of countries where Portuguese is an official language|Portuguese-speaking nation]] will host these events, and the third time the Olympics will be held in a Southern Hemisphere city.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/8282518.stm |title=BBC Sport, Rio to stage 2016 Olympic Games |work=BBC News |date=2 October 2009|accessdate=4 October 2009}}</ref> The Maracanã Stadium held the finals of the [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950]] and [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]s, the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup]], and the [[2007 Pan American Games|XV Pan American Games]] including its [[2007 Pan American Games opening ceremony|opening]] and closing ceremonies. Rio de Janeiro also hosted [[World Youth Day 2013|World Youth Day]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicculture.org/news/headlines/index.cfm?storyid=11247 |title=Latest Headlines : Pope will attend WYD in Rio in 2013, mayor claims |publisher=Catholic Culture |date=2 August 2011 |accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref>


